04074nam a22004575i 9780228002789DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20202020xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280027897 a10.1515/97802280027892doi  a(DE-B1597)656487  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aHIS0410002bisacsh04a972.94/032231 aLe Glaunec, Jean-Pierre, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Cry of Vertières :bLiberation Memory and the Beginning of Haiti /cJean-Pierre Le Glaunec. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource :b17 photos, 1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's French Atlantic Worlds Series ;v500tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tForeword by Lyonel Trouillot -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: To Arms, Citizens! -- tThe Battle of Vertières or “The Destiny of a Memory” -- tThe Final Act of an Atlantic Revolution -- tAttempt at Reconstruction -- tThe History of a Word That Doesn’t Really Exist -- t“The Last of the Whites” -- t“As Long as There’s One Negro Left” -- tThe Symbol of Haiti’s Strength and Survival -- tA Recent Place of Memory -- tPicolet, Fossé Capois, Vertières: In the Footsteps of Ancestors -- tConclusion: The Cry of Capois-la-Mort -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book tells the story of the Battle of Vertières, fought in 1803 between indigenous Haitian forces under the leadership of Jean-Jacques Dessalines and a French expeditionary army commanded by Napoleon. The battle marked the culmination of a thirteen-year revolutionary struggle to end slavery and the dawn of an independent Haiti. Yet despite its pivotal importance to the history of Haiti, France, and the Americas, the Battle of Vertières has been struck from the record. The Cry of Vertières is the first book-length study of the battle, drawing from an array of sources including military correspondence, Haitian literature, art, and popular music. The event itself is recounted in vivid detail: it is a dramatic story of a volunteer army of former slaves, seeking the promises of freedom and citizenship held out by the revolution, defeating a colonial power determined to re-enslave them. The book also examines why the history of the battle has been suppressed in France - an act of erasure of a humiliating defeat - and why it remains fragile even in Haiti. Jean-Pierre Le Glaunec explains that today Vertières is both a key lieu de mémoire that embodies reconciliation, pride, and strength for the Haitian people, and a figure of speech exploited by politicians to reinforce their power. Describing a decisive yet largely forgotten moment in the revolutionary history of the Americas, The Cry of Vertières makes an essential contribution to the complex subjects of race, memory, colonialism, and cultural nationalism in present-day France and Haiti.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aHISTORY / Caribbean & West Indies / General.2bisacsh1 aKaplansky, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978022800278940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228002789423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228002789/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles